0591: F716         ;============================================================================;
0592: F716         ;	List output  BIOS 05                                                     ;
0593: F716         ;                                                                            ;
0594: F716         ;  LIST is similar to CONOUT except that it sends the character in register  ;
0595: F716         ; C to the list device. It too checks first that the list device is ready to ;
0596: F716         ; receive the character. LIST is called by the CCP in response to the        ;
0597: F716         ; CONTROL-P toggle for printer echo of console output, and by the BDOS when	 ;
0598: F716         ; a program makes a Write Printer Byte or Display String call                ;
0599: F716         ; (LISTOUT and PRINTS, codes 5 and 9).                                       ;
0600: F716         ;                                                                            ;
0601: F716         ; This is a blocking routine                                                 ;
0602: F716         ;                                                                            ;
0603: F716         ;			Entry Point  	:	BiosStart + (5 *  3.)  (00FH)                ;
0604: F716         ;			Entry Parameters:	C = ASCII character to be sent to List Device;
0605: F716         ;			Exit Parameters :	None										 ;
0606: F716         ;============================================================================;
0607: F716
0608: F716             LIST:
0609: F716 3A 03 00               LD     A,(IOBYTE)
0610: F719 07                     RLCA                        ; move bits 7,6
0611: F71A 07                     RLCA                        ; to 1,0
0612: F71B DD 21 EB F7               LD     IX,LST_Vector
0613: F71F 18 E6                  JR     GenericOutStatus     ; go to generic blocking out routine
0614: F721
0615: F721         ;============================================================================;
0616: F721         ;	Punch output  BIOS 06                                                    ;
0617: F721         ;                                                                            ;
0618: F721         ;  PUNCH sends the character in register C to the "punch" device. As         ;
0619: F721         ; mentioned earlier, the "punch" is rarely a real paper tape punch.          ;
0620: F721         ; In most BIOS's, the PUNCH entry point either returns immediately and is    ;
0621: F721         ; effectively a null routine, or it outputs the character to a               ;
0622: F721         ; communications device, such as a; modem, on your computer. PUNCH must      ;
0623: F721         ; check that the "punch" device is indeed ready to accept another character  ;
0624: F721         ; for output, and must wait if it is not.                                    ;
0625: F721         ;                                                                            ;
0626: F721         ;  Digital Research's documentation states that the character to be output   ;
0627: F721         ; will always have its most significant bit set to O. This is not true.      ;
0628: F721         ; The BDOS simply transfers control over to the PUNCH entry point in the     ;
0629: F721         ; BIOS the setting of the most significant bit will be determined by the     ;
0630: F721         ; program making the BDOS function request (PUNOUT, code 4). This is         ;
0631: F721         ; important because the requirement of a zero would preclude being able to   ;
0632: F721         ; send pure  binary data via the BIOS PUNCH function                         ;
0633: F721         ;                                                                            ;
0634: F721         ; This is a blocking routine                                                 ;
0635: F721         ;                                                                            ;
0636: F721         ;			Entry Point  	:	BiosStart + (6 *  3).  (012H)                ;
0637: F721         ;			Entry Parameters:	C = ASCII character to be sent toPunch Device;
0638: F721         ;			Exit Parameters :	None										 ;
0639: F721         ;============================================================================;
0640: F721
0641: F721             PUNCH:                          ; Punch output
0642: F721 3A 03 00               LD     A,(IOBYTE)
0643: F724 0F                     RRCA
0644: F725 0F                     RRCA
0645: F726 0F                     RRCA                        ; move bits 5,4
0646: F727 0F                     RRCA                        ; to 1,0
0647: F728 DD 21 E3 F7               LD     IX,PUN_Vector
0648: F72C 18 D9                  JR     GenericOutStatus     ; go to generic blocking out routine
0649: F72E
0650: F72E         ;============================================================================;
0651: F72E         ;	Reader input  BIOS 07                                                    ;
0652: F72E         ;                                                                            ;
0653: F72E         ;  As with the PUNCH entry point, the READER entry point rarely connects to  ;
0654: F72E         ; a real paper tape reader.                                                  ;
0655: F72E         ; The READER function must return the next character from the reader device  ;
0656: F72E         ; in the A register, waiting, if need be, until there is a character.        ;
0657: F72E         ;                                                                            ;
0658: F72E         ;  Digital Research's documentation again says that the most significant bit ;
0659: F72E         ; of the A register must be 0, but this is not the case if you wish to       ;
0660: F72E         ; receive pure binary information via this function.                         ;
0661: F72E         ;                                                                            ;
0662: F72E         ;  READER is called whenever a program makes a Read "Reader" Byte function   ;
0663: F72E         ; request (READIN, code 3).                                                  ;
0664: F72E         ;                                                                            ;
0665: F72E         ; This is a blocking routine                                                 ;
0666: F72E         ;                                                                            ;
0667: F72E         ;			Entry Point  	:	BiosStart + (7 *  3).  (015H)                ;
0668: F72E         ;			Entry Parameters:	None										 ;
0669: F72E         ;			Exit Parameters :	A = ASCII character read from Reader Device	 ;
0670: F72E         ;============================================================================;
0671: F72E
0672: F72E             READER:                         ; Reader Input
0673: F72E 3A 03 00               LD     A,(IOBYTE)
0674: F731 0F                     RRCA
0675: F732 0F                     RRCA                        ; move bits 3,2  to 1,0
0676: F733 DD 21 DB F7               LD     IX,RDR_Vector
0677: F737             READER1:
0678: F737 CD E9 F6               CALL   GenericInStatus
0679: F73A 28 FB                  JR     Z,READER1            ; loop until there is some data to read
0680: F73C
0681: F73C DD 6E 06               LD     L,(IX+DataReadIndex)
0682: F73F DD 66 07               LD     H,(IX+(DataReadIndex+1))
0683: F742 E9                     JP     (HL)
0684: F743
0685: F743         ;============================================================================;
0686: F743         ;	List Status:  BIOS 0F                                                    ;
0687: F743         ;                                                                            ;
0688: F743         ;  LISTST was added when CP/M was upgraded from version 1.4 to version 2.0.  ;
0689: F743         ; This function returns the current status of the list device, using the     ;
0690: F743         ; IOBYTE if necessary to select the correct physical device. It sets the A   ;
0691: F743         ; register to OFFH if the list device can accept another character for       ;
0692: F743         ; output or to OOH if it is not ready. Digital Research's documentation      ;
0693: F743         ; states that this function is used by the DESPOOL utility program (which    ;
0694: F743         ; allows you to print a file "simultaneously" with other operations) to      ;
0695: F743         ; improve console response during its operation, and that it is acceptable   ;
0696: F743         ; for the routine always to return OOH if you choose not to implement it     ;
0697: F743         ; fully. Unfortunately, this statement is wrong. Many other programs use     ;
0698: F743         ; the LISTST function to "poll" the list device to make sure it is ready,    ;
0699: F743         ; and if it fails to come ready after a predetermined time, to output a      ;
0700: F743         ; message to the console; indicating that the printer is not ready. If you   ;
0701: F743         ; ever make a call to the BDOS list output functions, Write Printer Byte     ;
0702: F743         ; and Print String (codes 5 and 9), and the printer is not ready,            ;
0703: F743         ; then CP/M will wait forever-and your program will have lost control so     ;
0704: F743         ; it cannot even detect that the problem has occurred. If LISTST always      ;
0705: F743         ; returns a OOH, then the printer will always appear not to be ready.        ;
0706: F743         ; Not only does this make nonsense out of the LISTST function, but it also   ;
0707: F743         ; causes a stream of false "Printer not Ready" error messages to appear      ;
0708: F743         ; on the console.											                 ;
0709: F743         ;                                                                            ;
0710: F743         ;			Entry Point  	:	BiosStart + (F *  3).  (02DH)                ;
0711: F743         ;			Entry Parameters:	None										 ;
0712: F743         ;			Exit Parameters :	A = 0FFH if List Device is ready        	 ;
0713: F743         ;			                    A = 00H  if List Device is  not ready     	 ;
0714: F743         ;============================================================================;
0715: F743
